---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="FraiseQL vs Prisma - Detailed Comparison"
  description="Compare FraiseQL (compiled GraphQL) vs Prisma (ORM with generated client). Understand when to choose each."
>
  <div style="padding: 2rem; max-width: 1280px; margin: 0 auto;">
    <h1>FraiseQL vs Prisma</h1>
    <p style="font-size: 1.1rem; color: #666;">
      Two different approaches to database abstraction: GraphQL-first vs type-safe client.
    </p>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>The Core Difference</h2>
      <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1rem 0;">
        <tr style="background: #f5f3ff;">
          <th style="padding: 1rem; text-align: left; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"></th>
          <th style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">FraiseQL</th>
          <th style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Prisma</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>What It Is</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">GraphQL execution engine with database compilation</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">ORM with generated type-safe client</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: #fafafa;">
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>Client Interface</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">GraphQL queries and mutations</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">JavaScript/TypeScript ORM methods</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>Query Language</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">GraphQL (standard, language-agnostic)</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">TypeScript/JavaScript DSL (Node.js only)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: #fafafa;">
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>Database abstraction</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">SQL generation at compile time</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Runtime ORM with lazy query building</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>Use Case</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">APIs (internal or external GraphQL)</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Backend applications, microservices</td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>When to Choose Prisma</h2>
      <ul style="font-size: 1.05rem;">
        <li>
          <strong>Node.js backend applications</strong> – Building microservices, serverless functions, REST APIs
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Developer ergonomics priority</strong> – Type-safe client with autocompletion and intellisense
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Rapid prototyping</strong> – Quick CRUD generation from schema
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Multi-database support</strong> – PostgreSQL, MySQL, SQLite, SQL Server, MongoDB from one schema
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Internal APIs</strong> – Backend services with typed client consumption
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Learning TypeScript/database concepts</strong> – Great for onboarding junior developers
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p style="margin-top: 1rem; padding: 1rem; background: #f0fdf4; border-left: 4px solid #059669; border-radius: 4px;">
        <strong>✅ Good Fit:</strong> Node.js microservices, REST API backends, serverless functions, internal tools, applications where type safety is priority.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>When to Choose FraiseQL</h2>
      <ul style="font-size: 1.05rem;">
        <li>
          <strong>GraphQL APIs (external or high-scale)</strong> – Publishing GraphQL schema to clients
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Performance-critical systems</strong> – Need deterministic query execution, &lt;5ms latency
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Language-agnostic clients</strong> – Clients in Python, Go, Rust, mobile apps, etc.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Compliance requirements</strong> – HIPAA, SOC 2, 100% audit trail needed
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Analytics workloads</strong> – Large result sets, Arrow Flight streaming, complex aggregations
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Complex query planning</strong> – Need compile-time optimization to prevent N+1
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p style="margin-top: 1rem; padding: 1rem; background: #fef2f2; border-left: 4px solid #dc2626; border-radius: 4px;">
        <strong>✅ Good Fit:</strong> Public GraphQL APIs, compliance-heavy systems, performance-critical platforms, analytics APIs, multi-language client support.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Technical Comparison</h2>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Query Building</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Prisma:</strong> Runtime query building with fluent API
      </p>
      <pre><code>{`const user = await prisma.user.findUnique({
  where: { id: 1 },
  include: {
    posts: {
      include: { comments: true }
    }
  }
});
// Prisma generates SQL at runtime`}</code></pre>
      <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">
        <strong>FraiseQL:</strong> Compile-time query definition, runtime execution
      </p>
      <pre><code>{`query GetUserWithPosts($id: ID!) {
  user(id: $id) {
    id
    name
    posts {
      id
      title
      comments {
        id
        text
      }
    }
  }
}
// Query compiled to optimized SQL at build time`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Performance</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Prisma:</strong> ~5-20ms per query (includes runtime query planning and execution). Add latency for complex nested queries.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>FraiseQL:</strong> ~1-2ms per query (pre-compiled, execution only). Deterministic regardless of query complexity.
      </p>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">N+1 Query Prevention</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Prisma:</strong> Prevention via `include`/`select` planning. Developer responsible – easy to miss.
      </p>
      <p style="margin-top: 0.5rem;">
        Risk: Forgot to `include` a nested relation → N+1 queries at runtime.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>FraiseQL:</strong> Impossible to write N+1 queries. Compiler generates optimal SQL joins.
      </p>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Database Support</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Prisma:</strong> PostgreSQL, MySQL, SQLite, SQL Server, MongoDB. Same ORM client for all.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>FraiseQL:</strong> PostgreSQL, MySQL, SQLite, SQL Server. Compiles per-database SQL optimizations.
      </p>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Client Ecosystem</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Prisma:</strong> JavaScript/TypeScript only. Need REST/GraphQL adapter for other languages.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>FraiseQL:</strong> GraphQL clients in 16+ languages (JavaScript, Python, Go, Rust, Swift, Kotlin, etc.). Native support.
      </p>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Auditability</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Prisma:</strong> No built-in audit logging. Mutations are just database statements. Compliance requires external audit system.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>FraiseQL:</strong> 100% mutation audit trail built-in. Cryptographic signing, immutable logs. HIPAA/SOC2 ready.
      </p>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Schema Evolution</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Prisma:</strong> Schema changes via Prisma migrations. Generate and deploy. Relatively simple.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>FraiseQL:</strong> Schema changes via recompilation. Caught by compiler before deployment. Zero-downtime deploys via blue/green.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Real-World Scenarios</h2>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Scenario: Node.js REST API (Internal Use)</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Requirements:</strong> Fast internal REST API, type-safe database queries in TypeScript.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Prisma:</strong> ✅ Perfect. Fluent ORM, auto-generated types, migrations built-in.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>FraiseQL:</strong> ❌ Overkill. GraphQL layer not needed for internal REST API.
      </p>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Scenario: Public GraphQL API (100 req/sec SLA)</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Requirements:</strong> GraphQL clients in 5+ languages (Python, Go, Rust, Swift, etc.). SLA &lt;5ms.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Prisma:</strong> ❌ Not a GraphQL server. Would need Apollo Server + custom resolvers + cross-language SDK generation.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>FraiseQL:</strong> ✅ Native. GraphQL server built-in, 1-2ms latency, SDK generation for all languages.
      </p>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Scenario: Compliance-Heavy App (HIPAA)</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Requirements:</strong> Field-level encryption, 100% audit trail of all data access.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Prisma:</strong> ⚠️ Possible but would need extensive custom work. Need to add audit logging to every Prisma query.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>FraiseQL:</strong> ✅ Built-in. 100% mutation trail, field-level encryption, compliance-ready.
      </p>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Scenario: Serverless Functions (AWS Lambda)</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Requirements:</strong> Multiple Lambda functions, each handles part of API. Type-safe database access.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Prisma:</strong> ✅ Excellent. Each Lambda gets Prisma client, benefits from connection pooling, type safety.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>FraiseQL:</strong> ⚠️ Works but suboptimal. GraphQL execution engine better suited for single endpoint than distributed Lambda functions.
      </p>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Scenario: Analytics Data API (100K+ row results)</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Requirements:</strong> Stream large result sets efficiently, 40% compression, memory efficiency.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Prisma:</strong> ❌ Not optimized for this. Prisma client buffers all results.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>FraiseQL:</strong> ✅ Built for this. fraiseql-wire (200K× memory efficiency), Arrow Flight streaming, compression.
      </p>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Scenario: Multi-Tenant SaaS (PostgreSQL + MySQL Tenants)</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Requirements:</strong> Some customers on PostgreSQL, others on MySQL. Single API code.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Prisma:</strong> ⚠️ Possible but complex. Would need tenant routing logic + conditional Prisma client creation per database type.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>FraiseQL:</strong> ✅ Native. One schema compiles to both PostgreSQL and MySQL SQL. Tenant routing at runtime.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Ecosystem Comparison</h2>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Prisma Ecosystem</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Prisma Client – ORM with type generation</li>
        <li>Prisma Migrate – Database migrations</li>
        <li>Prisma Studio – GUI for database exploration</li>
        <li>Prisma Accelerate – Connection pooling (paid)</li>
        <li>Prisma Pulse – Real-time change subscriptions (paid)</li>
        <li>Strong TypeScript ecosystem integration</li>
      </ul>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">FraiseQL Ecosystem</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>fraiseql – GraphQL execution engine</li>
        <li>fraiseql-wire – Memory-efficient streaming (200K×)</li>
        <li>confiture – Fast migrations (600×)</li>
        <li>pg_tviews – Incremental views (2,083×)</li>
        <li>fraiseql-seed – Test data generation (300×)</li>
        <li>fraisier – Deployment orchestration</li>
        <li>velocitybench – Performance benchmarking</li>
        <li>11 tools total, designed to multiply each other's performance</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Honest Tradeoffs</h2>
      <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1rem 0;">
        <tr style="background: #f5f3ff;">
          <th style="padding: 1rem; text-align: left; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Dimension</th>
          <th style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">FraiseQL Advantage</th>
          <th style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Prisma Advantage</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>Client Support</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">✅ 16+ languages</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">JavaScript/TypeScript only</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: #fafafa;">
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>Developer Experience</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">GraphQL learning required</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">✅ Fluent TypeScript API</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>Performance</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">✅ 1-2ms deterministic</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">5-20ms variable</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: #fafafa;">
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>N+1 Prevention</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">✅ Impossible</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Developer responsible</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>Compliance Ready</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">✅ Built-in audit trail</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Requires custom work</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: #fafafa;">
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>Setup Complexity</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Compilation pipeline</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">✅ Simple npm install</td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Complementary Use</h2>
      <p>
        Consider using <strong>both</strong> tools strategically:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Internal Services (Prisma)</strong> – Backend microservices and internal REST APIs use Prisma for type-safe database access.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Public API (FraiseQL)</strong> – Expose a public GraphQL API via FraiseQL on top of the same database.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Shared Database</strong> – Both connect to the same PostgreSQL, complementing each other's strengths.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p style="margin-top: 1rem; color: #666;">
        Example architecture: Microservices use Prisma for internal REST APIs, external GraphQL API via FraiseQL on the same database.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Migration Considerations</h2>

      <p>
        <strong>Migrating from Prisma to FraiseQL:</strong> Schema can be extracted from Prisma schema.prisma → FraiseQL Python/TypeScript decorators. Takes 1-2 weeks depending on complexity.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Migrating from FraiseQL to Prisma:</strong> Not typically recommended – they solve different problems. FraiseQL is GraphQL API optimization, Prisma is backend ORM.
      </p>
    </section>

    <p style="margin-top: 3rem;">
      <a href="/vs">← Back to Comparisons</a> | <a href="/">Home</a>
    </p>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
